title: year_of_the_pig

The Pig is the last of 12 animals representing the Chinese zodiac. The following are years of the Pig: 1935, 1947, 1959, 1971, [[1983]], [[1995]], [[2007]], [[2019]], 2031.

A [[year of the dog|Dog year]] always comes before the [b]Year of the Pig[/b], and a [[year of the rat|Rat year]] always comes afterwards in the next 12-year Chinese zodiac animal cycle.

In Japan, the wild [[boar]] is used instead of the (domesticated) pig.

title: stray_(game)
body:
[b]STRAY[/b] is a 2022 [[cyberpunk]] adventure [[video game]] developed by BlueTwelve Studio and published by "Annapurna Interactive":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annapurna_Interactive . 

The story follows [[ginger_(stray)|a stray cat]] who falls into a walled city populated by [[robot]]s, machines, and mutant [[monster]] bacteria, and sets out to return to the surface with the help of a drone companion, [[b-12_(stray)|B-12]]. 

The game is presented through a third-person perspective. The player traverses the game world by leaping across platforms and climbing up obstacles, and can interact with the environment to open new paths. Using B-12, they can store items found throughout the world and hack into technology to solve puzzles. Throughout the game, the player must evade the antagonistic [[zurk_(stray)|Zurks]] and [[guardian_(stray)|Sentinels]], which attempt to kill them.

Stray was announced in 2020 and became highly anticipated. It was released for [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation 5]], and Windows in July 2022, and for [[Xbox One]] and [[Xbox Series X]]/S in August 2023; a macOS version is in development. 

The game received generally positive reviews, with praise for its artistic design, [[cat]] gameplay, narrative, original score, and platforming elements, though critics were divided on the combat and stealth sequences. Stray received accolades at The Game Awards, Game Developers Choice Awards, and Golden Joystick Awards, and appeared on multiple publications' year-end lists. An animated film adaptation is currently in development.

title: mount_suribachi

[b]Mount Suribachi[/b] (æ‘ºé‰¢å±±, [i]Suribachiyama[/i]) is a 169-metre (554 ft)-high mountain on the southwest end of [[Iwo Jima]] in the northwest Pacific Ocean under the administration of Ogasawara Subprefecture, [[Tokyo (city)|]] Metropolis, [[Japan]].

The mountain's name derives from its shape, resembling a suribachi or grinding bowl. It is also known as "Mount Pipe" (ãƒ‘ã‚¤ãƒ—å±±, [i]paipu-yama[/i]), since the volcanic gas and water vapor that rolls in from the summit, alongside the rest of the island, give the appearance of a smoking pipe when viewed from the sea.

Joe Rosenthal's iconic [[World War II]] photograph, [[Raising the Flag on Iwo Jima]], depicting [[united states marine corps|United States Marines]] raising an American flag, was taken at the mountain's peak during the Battle of Iwo Jima in 1945. Ammunition ship [i]USS Suribachi[/i] was named after this mountain.

title: hudson
body:
[b]Hudson Soft Co., Ltd.[/b] was a Japanese [[video game]] company that released numerous games for video [[game console]]s, home computers and mobile phones, mainly from the 1980s to the 2000s. It was headquartered in the Midtown Tower in Tokyo Midtown, Akasaka, Minato, [[Tokyo (city)|]], [[Japan]], with an additional office in the Hudson Building in Sapporo.

Hudson Soft was founded on May 18, 1973. Initially, it dealt with personal computer products, but later expanded to the development and publishing of video games, mobile content, video game peripherals and music recording. 

Primarily a video game publisher, it internally developed many of the video games it released while outsourcing others to external companies. It is known for series such as [[Bomberman]], [[Takahashi Meijin no Bouken Jima|Adventure Island]], [[Star Soldier]], and [[PC-Genjin|Bonk]]. Hudson also developed video games released by other publishers such as the Mario Party series from Nintendo.

Hudson Soft made the [[PC Engine]]/TurboGrafx-16 in association with [[NEC Corporation]], to compete against [[Nintendo]], [[SEGA]], and [[SNK]], while continuing making games on other platforms as a third-party developer.

The mascot of the company is a [[bee]] named [[Hachisuke]]. Hudson Soft ceased to exist as a company on March 1, 2012, and merged with [[Konami]] Digital Entertainment, which was the surviving entity. Konami owns the assets of Hudson and has since rereleased its video game back catalogue on different occasions.

title: nec_corporation
body:
[b]NEC Corporation[/b] (æ—¥æœ¬é›»æ°—æ ªå¼ä¼šç¤¾, [i]Nippon Denki Kabushiki-gaisha[/i]) is a [[Japan]]ese multinational information technology and electronics corporation, headquartered in Minato, [[Tokyo (city)|]]. 

The company was known as the [b]Nippon Electric Company, Limited[/b], before rebranding in 1983 as [b]NEC[/b]. It provides IT and network solutions, including cloud computing, artificial intelligence (AI), Internet of things (IoT) platform, and telecommunications equipment and software, to business enterprises, communications services providers and to government agencies, and has also been the biggest Personal [[Computer]] vendor in Japan since the 1980s, when it launched the PC-8000 series.

In 1987, NEC licensed technology from [[Hudson]] Soft, a video game manufacturer, to create a video [[game console]] called the [[PC Engine]] (later released in 1989 as the TurboGrafx-16 in the North American market). While the PC Engine achieved a considerable following, it has been said that NEC held a much stronger influence on the video game industry through its role as a leading semiconductor manufacturer than through any of its direct [[video game]] products.

NEC was the world's fourth-largest PC manufacturer by 1990. Its semiconductors business unit was the world's largest semiconductor company by annual revenue from 1985 to 1992, the second largest in 1995, one of the top three in 2000, and one of the top 10 in 2006. NEC spun off its semiconductor business to Renesas Electronics and Elpida Memory. Once Japan's major electronics company, NEC has largely withdrawn from manufacturing since the beginning of the 21st century.

NEC was #463 on the 2017 Fortune 500 list. NEC is a member of the Sumitomo Group.

title: jimmy_doolittle
body:
Honorary General [b]James Harold Doolittle[/b] was an [[United States|American]] military general and aviation pioneer.

Best known for the eponymous [i]Doolittle Raid[/i], a daring bombing raid on [[Tokyo (city)|]] on 18 April 1942 during [[World War II]]. Whilst the raid caused minimal damage, it greatly affected the Japanese military to take more cautious stance against enemy air raids, which were often cited as a contributing factor in the American victory at the [[Battle of Midway]]. After the raid, he would serve as a bomber group commander over both theatres of the war.

In shipgirl context, he is usually paired with a personification of USS [[Hornet (kancolle)|]], the ship that his [[B-25 Mitchell]] bombers took off from during the raid.

title: tiananmen_square
body:
A city square in the center of [[Beijing]], [[China]]. Located between the eponymous Tiananmen gate and the [[Forbidden City]].

The site, and the gate to an extent, has significant political significance for the modern history of China. Oversaw the events spanning from the Opium war and Boxer rebellion in 19th century, the declaration of the founding of the PRC in 1949, and the site of the Tiananmen Square protest in 1989.

Outside of China, the square is best known for being the site of the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre, to which anti-CCP dissident refers to it simply as 8964 (the date of the crackdown in year/month/day format).

title: nekketsu_kouha_kunio-kun
body:
The first game in the [[Kunio-kun series]].

[i][b]Nekketsu KÅha Kunio-kun[/b][/i] (ç†±è¡€ç¡¬æ´¾ãã«ãŠãã‚“, [i]Hot-Blooded Tough Guy Kunio[/i]) is a 1986 Japanese [[arcade]] [[video game]] where the player takes control of a high school boy called [[Kunio-kun]] as he fights against the various gangs who bully his friend, Hiroshi, at the start of each stage.

The original arcade game was created by "Kishimoto Yoshihisa":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoshihisa_Kishimoto and developed by "Technos Japan":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Techn%C5%8Ds_Japan (who would become famous for the [[Double Dragon]] series) and published by [[Taito]].

The international version, renamed [i][b]Renegade[/b][/i], features changed graphics and dubbed voices that gives the game a more western-looking setting. The plot was also changed from Kunio beating gangs to avenge his friend to the main hero having to rescue his girlfriend. [i]Renegade[/i] itself would spawn two sequels in Europe.

The game was ported to the [[Nintendo]] [[Famicom]] home console in early 1987 and to the western [[NES]] at the end of the same year. It was released for the [[PlayStation 2]] in Japan as part of the Ore-tachi Game Center Zoku lineup on January 26, 2006.

title: anaconda_vice
body:
A [[submission hold]] innovated by [[New Japan Pro Wrestling|NJPW]] wrestler Tenzan Hiroyoshi and also used by [[All Elite Wrestling]] alumnus and current [[WWE]] wrestler [[CM Punk]].

The Anaconda Vice is done from a position in which the wrestler and the opponent are seated on the mat facing each other. The wrestler sits on one side of the opponent and using his near arm encircles the opponent in a headlock position and grabs the opponent's near wrist, bending the arm upwards. Then, the wrestler maneuvers his/her other arm through the "hole" created by the opponent's bent wrist, locks his/her hand upon his/her own wrist, and then pulls the opponent forward, causing pressure on the opponent's arm and neck.

It can also be spelled as [b]Anaconda Vise[/b] and its technical name is [i]Arm-Trap Triangle Choke[/i].

title: suika_game
body:
A puzzle game developed by AladdinX where you merge fruits to create a [[watermelon]] ([i]suika[/i] in Japanese). Similar to the game "2048". The player drops a random fruit into a box. Fruits of the same type will merge into a different larger fruit, with the largest fruit being a watermelon. The game ends if the fruits overflow the box.

You start with the [[Cherry]] as the smallest fruit, then later on [[Strawberry]], [[Grapes]], [[Dekopon (fruit)|]], [[Persimmon]]s, [[Apple]]s, [[Nashi Pear|Pear]]s, [[Peach]]es, [[Pineapple]], [[Melon]]/[[Cantaloupe]], and finally, Watermelon.

The game has gained sudden popularity after it was played by various Japanese [[virtual YouTuber]]s, though controversy after the developers forbade the clipping of the gameplay footage by third parties later caused the VTubers to switch to fan games/clones instead. The ban has since been lifted.

title: mazinger_z
body:
[i][b]Mazinger Z[/b][/i] (ãƒã‚¸ãƒ³ã‚¬ãƒ¼Z [i]MajingÄ Zetto[/i]) is a classic and extremely influential and popular giant [[super robot]] manga that ran in [i]Weekly Shonen Jump[/i] from 1972 until 1973. The series was created by [[Nagai Gou]] (Kiyoshi Nagai).

The story tells the adventures of [[Kabuto Kouji]], the young brave pilot of Mazinger Z, a powerful [[mecha]] with super powers that fights against evil hostile giant [[robot]]s called "mechanical [[monster|beasts]]".

Due to its popularity the original manga was turned into a 92 episode anime that debuted also in late 1972 and ended in 1974. It has spawned several notable sequels and spinoff series, among them [[UFO Robo Grendizer]], [[Mazinkaiser]], and [[Robot Girls Z]].

Mazinger Z was broadcast in several countries and became very famous worldwide. Its fame in some European countries was such that even "a giant statue of the titular robot":http://trip-n-travel.com/listicle/16496/ was erected in the province of Tarragona, [[Spain]], in the year 1979. 

It was also a very popular anime in [[Mexico]] during the 1980s, where it was dubbed into [[spanish_text|Spanish]] directly from the Japanese version, keeping all the original Japanese character names intact and broadcasting all the complete 92 episodes, unlike the version later aired in the [[united_states|U.S.]] (which was called [i][b]Tranzor Z[/b][/i] and was not very popular due to its severe censorship and many absent episodes).

Mexican director [[Guillermo del Toro]] has cited this show as a very important influence on his movie [[Pacific Rim]]. The comic [[Karmatron y los Transformables]] was also heavily influenced by Mazinger.

This tag should be used for the original manga/anime and related media. For the franchise as a whole use [[Mazinger (series)]].

title: indian_elephant
body:
The Indian elephant ([i]Elephas maximus indicus[/i]) is one of three extant recognized subspecies of the Asian [[elephant]] and native to mainland Asia.

In general, Asian elephants are smaller than [[African elephant|African elephants]] and have smaller ears, but relatively broader skulls and larger trunks than African elephants.

Notably, one of these elephants were mentioned in [[Pokedex]] entries for [[Raichu]] and [[Gastly]], despite the near-total absence of real life animals in [[Pokemon]].

body:
The second remodels/kai ni of [i][[Kantai Collection]][/i]'s [[Houshou (Kancolle)|]], as seen in post #5878341 for standard kai ni and post #5878299 for E version.

Released 06 December 2022, her kai ni comes in two forms: standard kai ni and a transport "E" version. She keeps her usual [[Japanese clothes|traditional outfit]] from base form in her standard kai ni but gains a white [[hair ribbon]], large white [[sash]] ([i]these two are the most obvious changes to note if she's not depicted with her rig or in her E version[/i]), and a 28 cm [[anti-aircraft gun|rocket launcher]] on her [[quiver]], while her [[flight deck]] gains a catapult (faintly seen). 

Her "E" version swaps her base outfit in favor of a [[green kimono]] meant to represent her real-life camouflage pattern, while she holds a daihatsu amphibious landing craft.

In remodeling Houshou from kai to kai ni, a prototype catapult is required as she never received any upgrade after 1944 (when she was modified to handle heavier aircraft for training purposes), and never received any aircraft catapult.

title: blood_bag
body:
A small bag full of [[blood]], which has been collected from the patient or from a blood donor in order to replace that patient's blood should there be a lot of blood loss during surgery, or from exsanguination due to a critical [[injury]].

Different patients/donors' blood is collected, analyzed and grouped according to blood type, of which there are four: "A, B, AB, and O":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_blood_group_systems, depending upon inherited antigens. There is also the + and - status to indicate if the "Rh factor":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rh_blood_group_system (or Rhesus factor) is present.

Blood bags are often seen hanging from [[iv stand|intravenous stands]] in hospitals near the patient's bed.

title: geoduck
body:
A type of saltwater [[clam]] native to the west coast of North America.

The shell of the clam ranges from 15 centimeters (5.9 in) to over 20 centimeters (7.9 in) in length, but the extremely long siphons make the clam itself much longer than this, with the siphons alone being able to reach 1 meter (3.3 ft) in length. The geoduck is one of the largest clams in the world and one of the longest-lived animals in the world, with the oldest known specimen having lived 168 years.

Rather infamous for its [[phallic_symbol|phallic]] shape, which led into it became a delicacy and are believed to have aphodisaic properties.

title: enigma_(housamo)
body:
[[Tokyo Afterschool Summoners]] character
Designed by [[musou_luf|MusouLuf]]

A cryptographic life form born into a space beyond the bounds of the 23 other worlds. He was deciphered by the Guild Master of the Akihabara Creators and given an outer appearance and personality for interacting with the world at large. Specifically, in accordance with the preferences of the one he calls his creator, he's taken on the form of a mechanical Therian. His true form is immaterial, however, as Enigma's existence is comprised solely of data transmitted over the net. The upshot of this is that he's capable of self-reproducing with no limits beyond those of his own available resources, and each and every copy is individually customized and optimized for the service of a specific end user. This particular Enigma has been customized for use by the Guild Master of the Summoners, considering himself to be something of a secretary for his assigned master and adopting a vaguely condescending, highly intellectual persona in service to that end. The idea, it seems, is that he quite genuinely wishes to supplement the shortcomings of his master's ego, as calculated through careful observation and data-crunching, in order to prove his worth. This is very much in keeping with his self-proclaimed role, since the very word secretary is derived from secret, having long ago been used to refer to those who safeguarded the classified documents of the aristocracyâ€”a term which perfectly and succinctly fits the identity of this cryptographic Enigma like a glove. There is one particular Transient who's quite taken with Enigma, being extremely fond of puzzles and quizzes.

title: pluto_(manga)
body:
[b]PLUTO[/b] (ãƒ—ãƒ«ãƒ¼ãƒˆã‚¦, [i]PurÅ«tÅ[/i])  is a Japanese [[science fiction]], [[cyberpunk]] and detective manga series written and illustrated by [[Urasawa Naoki]] (of [[MONSTER (manga)|]] fame). 

It was serialized in Shogakukan's seinen manga magazine Big Comic Original from September 2003 to April 2009, with its chapters collected into eight tankÅbon volumes. The series is based on the [[Tezuka Osamu]]'s [[Tetsuwan Atom]]/[[atom (pluto)|Astro Boy]] classic manga series, specifically a reboot of "The Greatest Robot on Earth" (åœ°ä¸Šæœ€å¤§ã®ãƒ­ãƒœãƒƒãƒˆ, [i]ChijÅ Saidai no Robotto[/i]) story arc, and named after [[pluto (pluto (manga))|the arc's chief villain]]. 

Urasawa reinterprets the story as a suspenseful murder mystery starring [[Gesicht (pluto)|]], a Europol robot detective trying to solve the case of a string of [[robot]] and human deaths. 

Nagasaki Takashi is credited as the series' co-author. Tezuka Macoto, Tezuka Osamu's son, supervised the series, and Tezuka Productions is listed as having given cooperation. The series was licensed and released in English in North America by Viz Media under the name [b]PLUTO: Urasawa x Tezuka[/b]. 

PLUTO was a critical and commercial success, winning several awards, including the ninth Tezuka Osamu Cultural Prize, and selling over 8.5 million copies. An original net anime series, produced by Genco and Tezuka Productions, and animated by Studio M2, premiered on [[Netflix]] in 2023.

title: affliction_(darkest_dungeon)
body:
A commonly seen game mechanic in Darkest Dungeon 1 and 2, it appears over the heads of affected individuals who have succumbed to a severe negative emotion or madness. The affliction can be obtained from many of the game's stress-related mechanics and inflicts a negative effect on the afflicted individual.

It is often seen with its iconic black circular arc and five spike like protrusions, heading inwards, surrounded by a red hue floating above characters' heads to indicate they are currently plagued by said affliction. 

[spoilers]Through the many challenges that the heroes of Darkest Dungeon 2 go through, it is eventually revealed that its true name is: 'The Iron Crown', and is actually the entity responsible for causing many of Darkest Dungeon's abomination related disasters and spreading the corruption in the land.[/spoilers]

title: blade_runner
body:
A 1982 American [[science fiction]] film, directed by Ridley Scott and starring [[Harrison Ford]], [[Rutger Hauer]], [[Edward James Olmos]], [[Daryl Hannah]] and [[Sean Young]].

The screenplay, written by Hampton Fancher and David Peoples, is loosely based on the 1968 novel [[Do Androids Dream of Electric Sheep?]] by American sci-fi writer [[Philip K. Dick]].

While not initially a success with North American audiences, [i][b]Blade Runner[/b][/i] was very popular internationally and became a cult film. It was a hit in Japan, where it greatly influenced the "[[cyberpunk]]" look of later sci-fi anime and manga like [[Akira (manga)|]], [[Bubblegum Crisis]], [[Armitage III]], [[Ghost in the Shell]] and [[Appleseed]] among many many others. 

The movie's dark style and futuristic designs by [[Syd Mead]] have served as a benchmark and its influence can be seen in many subsequent science fiction films, anime, video games, and television programs.

A sequel called [[Blade Runner 2049]] was released in most countries on October 6, 2017. It was released in Japan on October 27, 2017.

title: snatcher
body:
[b]Snatcher[/b] (ã‚¹ãƒŠãƒƒãƒãƒ£ãƒ¼ [i]SunacchÄ[/i]) is a [[cyberpunk]] graphic adventure [[video game]] produced by [[Konami]], originally released in Japan for the NEC PC-8801 and MSX 2 computer platforms in 1988. 

It was followed by a CD-ROM remake released for the [[PC Engine]] video game console in 1992, which was subsequently ported and localized into English for the Mega-CD/[[Sega CD]] in 1994. 

Snatcher was the second video game written and directed by [[Kojima Hideo]], following the original [[metal_gear_(series)|Metal Gear]] for the MSX2. 

The game's futuristic story centers around a detective called [[Gillian Seed]], who is assigned to investigate a breed of [[android]]s known as "Snatchers", who are killing humans and taking their place in society. The game is known for its heavy influence from cult [[science fiction]] films such as [[Blade Runner]], [[Akira (manga)|]] and [[The Terminator]].

title: gondola
body:
A traditional passenger-carrying [[boat]] of Venice, Italy, measuring a law-regulated 10.85m in length and having an maximum breadth of 1.40m. It is often sculled by a single person standing on the rear deck, with the [[oar]] resting on an oarlock. Gondolas with multiple rowers also exist, an example being the [i]traghetto[/i] or ferry gondola. 

[i]Gondole[/i] can be differentiated from other boats by being asymmetrical, with one side being slightly longer than the other, and by the presence of a [i]ferro[/i], a stylized S-shaped bow ornament made of metal whose design represents elements of Venice and whose weight counterbalances that of the gondolier.

Gondolas figure prominently in [[Amano Kozue]]'s anime and manga series [[Aria (manga)|]].

title: tree-topper
body:
From Wikipedia:

A tree-topper or treetopper is a decorative ornament placed on the top (or "crown") of a Christmas tree. Tree-toppers can take any form, though the most common include a star (representing the Star of Bethlehem), finial, angel ("Christmas angel"), or fairy. Additional forms range from a paper rosette, ribbon bow, Father Christmas or Santa Claus, to a Christian cross, owl, white dove, spike, or sunburst.

Tree-toppers may be made of from a wide range of materials. Modern plastic tree-toppers are often electric and once connected with the tree's lights offer a gentle glow. Following World War II, various symbols of Christmastide, such as Santa Claus, were introduced as electrified tree-toppers.

title: tiger_(p)
body:
The [b]Porsche Tiger[/b], also known as the [b]VK4501(P)[/b] or [b]Tiger(P)[/b], was an unsuccessful heavy tank prototype produced by Porsche in [[Germany]] during 1942.

On the 21st May 1942 Henschel and Porsche at a meeting in Germany were asked to submit designs for a 45 ton heavy tank capable of mounting the high velocity 88mm KwK L/56 gun which was derived from the German [[88_flak|88mm flak gun]]. Both the Henschel and Porsche tanks were to be fitted with the same turret supplied by Krupp. The Porsche company worked on updating the VK3001P medium tank, Porsche's medium tank prototype, and adapted parts used on it for the new tank.

The new Porsche tank, designated the VK4501(P) was to be powered by twin air cooled gasoline Porsche Type 101/1 engines which were mounted to the rear of the tank. The twin engines would then drive two generators, one on either side of the tank, which would then power two motors which would drive the tracks. But the engine along with its drive system were very prone to break down and needed almost constant maintenance to keep the tank running. This and the tank being less maneuverable than its competitor was the reason why Henschel's prototype, the [[Tiger I]], was adopted for production instead.

Porsche AG had already manufactured about one hundred chassis of the unsuccessful Porsche Tiger that were no longer required. It was therefore decided that the Porsche chassis were to be used as the basis of a new heavy tank destroyer (the [[Elefant]]), mounting Krupp's newly developed 88 mm Pak 43/2 anti-tank gun.

title: gaza-c
body:
A fictional [[mecha]] from the [[Gundam]] series. It first appeared in [[Zeta Gundam]] from 1985.

The [b]AMX-003 Gaza-C[/b] is an early transformable [[mobile_suit|MS]] fielded by [[Haman Karn]]'s [[Neo Zeon]]. 

It was plagued by minor design flaws in its transformable frame and a rushed production due to Neo Zeon's low resources, but was sent into action anyway with satisfactory combat performance - the only major drawback being an incapacity of using the transformation system more than three times without breaking the fragile suit apart.

Refined into the more resilient [[Gaza-D]].

title: uchuu_no_senshi
body:
[b][i]Starship Troopers[/i][/b] (å®‡å®™ã®æˆ¦å£« [i]Uchuu No Senshi[/i], lit. "Soldiers of Space") is a six part anime OVA produced by Sunrise/Bandai Visual and released in 1988. It is based on the book [[Starship Troopers]] by Robert A. Heinlein that was published in 1959. 

This anime production is considered by many the "most faithful" to the original novel's plot, despite the fact that many liberties were taken with the characters and the original book's themes. For instance [[Johnny Rico]], an [[Asian]] [[philippines|Filipino]] in the novel, is a [[blonde_hair|blonde]] White [[argentina|Argentine]] in the OVA. 

Interestingly, the main character's ethnicity in the OVA series has more in common with Paul Verhoeven's 1997 film than the source material â€” this despite their productions being wholly unrelated and having nearly a decade of difference. However, unlike the 1997 film, the most prominent link the anime has to the original book are the inclusion of [[power armor]] and drop pods that were absent in Verhoeven's film.

[[Miyatake Kazutaka]] of Studio Nue originally designed the [[power suit]]s in the OVA for the Japanese edition of the 50s novel in the early 80s. The design also appeared uncredited in the [[Daicon III]] and [[Daicon IV]] fan made animated shorts in the early 80s, several years before the OVA was made.

title: pish
body:
A character from [[Kami Jigen Game Neptune V]], known as [b]Peashy[/b] in English localizations.

[[Personification]] of the [[PC Engine]]. Is not very smart and tends to use (childish) violence on others. Grows very attached to [[Neptune (neptunia)|]] and [[Pururut]], whom she calls "Neptuna" ("Neputenu" in the Japanese version) and "Ploot" ("Pururuto" in the Japanese version).

[spoiler]During the course of the game, she comes in contact with a CPU memory and is turned into a CPU without any of the protagonists knowing. Eventually, [[Anonedeath]], one of the Seven Sages, learns of this and changes part of her memory in order to turn her into a tool of the Seven Sages. Using her CPU form [[Yellow Heart (neptunia)|]] and a technical booster built by Anonydeath, she becomes a major problem for the protagonists. (And a frustration. Take a look at her CPU-forms bust size and you will know why). Later on, she can become an ally however.[/spoiler]

Voiced by: [[Yuuki Aoi]] (Japanese), Sandy Fox (English, games), Tia Ballard (English, anime)
